definition.value: A uridine 5'-phosphate that is the 5-(2-methoxy-2-oxoethyl) derivative of uridine 5'-monophosphate.
Uridine bearing an additional carboxymethyl substituent at position 5.
A uridine phosphate in which the uridine bears an additional carboxymethyl substituent at position 5 and the phosphono group is at the 5'-oxygen.
A glycosylglucose consisting of D-glucose with undefined anomeric stereochemistry and an alpha-D-glucosyl residue attached at the 3-position.
Any  metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in eukaryotes, the taxon that include members of the fungi, plantae and animalia kingdoms.
Any metabolite produced during a metabolic reaction in prokaryotes, the taxon that include members of domains such as the bacteria and archaea.

A compound of iron and sulfate in which the ratio of iron(2+) to sulfate ions is 1:1. Various hydrates occur naturally - most commonly the heptahydrate, which loses water to form the tetrahydrate at 57degreeC and the monohydrate at 65degreeC.

A hydrate that is the monohydrate form of iron(2+) sulfate. It is obtained from the heptahydrate by heating above 65degreeC. It is used as a source of iron in the treatment of iron-deficiency anaemia (generally in solid-dosage treatments; for liquid-dosage treatments, the heptahydrate is normally used).

A hydrate that is the heptahydrate form of iron(2+) sulfate. It is used as a source of iron in the treatment of iron-deficiency anaemia (generally in liquid-dosage treatments; for solid-dosage treatments, the monohydrate is normally used).
A sulfide mineral with formula AsFeS. It is the most abundant and widespread arsenic mineral.
A D-rhamnofuranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A carboxamide resulting from the formal condensation of a carboxylic acid with the nitrogen of an indole.
A L-fucoside with a beta-configuration.
An L-rhamnofuranose having alpha-configuration at the anomeric centre.
An iron molecular entity that is a compound or mineral containing iron and sulfur.
Any member of the class of iron sulfides in which the iron is in the (2+) oxidation state.
Any member of the class of iron sulfides in which the iron is in the (3+) oxidation state.
A polymer which has lost secondary or tertiary structure.
A very long-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of lacceroic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A very long-chain fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of geddic acid, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group.
A member of the class of chlorophyll that is chlorophyll a substituted at position 7(1) by a hydroxy group.
An L-rhamnofuranose having beta-configuration at the anomeric centre.
A D-rhamnofuranose having beta-configuration at the anomeric centre.
The furanose form of D-rhamnose.
A deuterated compound that is L-alanine in which the alpha-hydrogen and the three methyl hydrogens are replaced by deuterium.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 18:1 in which the acyl group is specified as oleoyl and is located at position 2.
A phosphatidylcholine 36:1 in which the phosphatidyl acyl groups at positions 1 and 2 are specified as oleoyl and stearoyl respectively.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 18:0 in which the acyl group is specified as stearoyl (octadecanoyl) and is located at position 2.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 16:0 in which the acyl group is specified as palmitoyl (hexadecanoyl) and is located at position 2.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 20:4 in which the acyl group is specified as arachidonoyl and is located at position 2.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 18:1 in which the acyl group is specified as oleoyl and is located at either position 1 or 2.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 18:2 in which the acyl group is specified as linoleoyl and is located at position 2.
A lysophosphatidylcholine 22:6 in which the acyl group is specified as (4Z,7Z,10Z,13Z,16Z,19Z)-docosahexaenoyl and is located at position 2.
Any molecular entity that has one or more hydrogen atoms replaced by deuterium.
A hydrate that is the hemihydrate form of bumadizone calcium. Used for treatment of rheumatoid arthritis.
A straight-chain alkane comprising of 29 carbon atoms.
Any phospholipid that contains an olefinic function.
A hydroxy fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any 2-hydroxy fatty acid.
A 2-hydroxy fatty acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any (R)-2-hydroxy fatty acid.
A hydrate that is the hexahydrate form of ferrous ammonium sulfate. Acts as an iron ion donor for building Fe-S clusters in vitro.

A sulfide salt with formula Na2S. The pentahydrate and  (particularly) the nonahydrate are also known. In gel form, sodium sulfide is used to soften toenails to assist in trimming (and so relive pain) of ingrowing toenails.
A hydrate with formula Na2S.9H2O.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid that is dotriacontane in which one of the methyl groups has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.
A straight-chain saturated fatty acid that is tetratriacontane in which one of the methyl groups has been oxidised to the corresponding carboxylic acid.
A ketone in which the carbonyl group is attached to an aromatic ring.
A hydrate that is the monohydrate of the sodium salt of meclofenamic acid. It is used for the treatment of dysmenorrhoea (painful periods), osteoarthritis and rheumatoid arthritis.
A compound of ammonium, iron and sulfate in which the ratio of ammonium to iron(2+) to sulfate ions is 2:1:2.
